S2.T1.caption: Table 1:  Entity definition and its statistics in our dataset. "Uni." means the number of unique entities, which equals to the length of gazetteer list.
references:
Table 1 shows the statistics of our dataset.
Our VietMed-NER contains 18 entity types across 9000 sentences, split into train-dev-test as 8-2-6 hours.
To the best of our knowledge, compared to all other public spoken NER datasets, ours has the largest number of entity types.

S3.T2.caption: Table 2:  Statistics of state-of-the-art pre-trained language models which we used for NER task.
references:
Table 2 shows the statistics of various pre-trained monolingual and multilingual models to fine-tune on our dataset.
Monolingual: PhoBERT_base, PhoBERT_large, PhoBERT_base-v2 Nguyen and Nguyen (2020); ViDeBERTa_base Tran et al. (2023), BARTpho Tran et al. (2021), ViT5 Phan et al. (2022),
Multilingual: XML-R_base, XML-R_large Conneau et al. (2020).
To our best knowledge, these are the best pre-trained models that achieved state-of-the-art results on various downstream tasks in the Vietnamese language, including NER.

S4.T3.caption:
Table 3:  NER results (in percent) on reference text of test set using various pre-trained language models. Metrics shown are Precision, Recall, and overall micro F1 score.
Results by entity types are shown in Appendix.
references:
Table 3 and 4 show results of NER using various pre-trained models.
The pre-trained monolingual model PhoBERT_base-v2 outperformed other monolingual models, at 61.99% of F1 score on reference text, and 51.29% on ASR output.
Even though it has fewer parameters than PhoBERT_large, it achieved equal performance probably due to the larger amount of pre-training data.
All pre-trained multilingual models outperformed monolingual models.
This gap can be explained by the larger amount of pre-training data (2.5TB of multilingual data for XLM-R compared to only 140GB of monolingual data for PhoBERT_base-v2).
Furthermore, encoder-based models perform, on average, better than seq2seq models, which could be due to the nature of seq2seq being generative, thus less suitable for NER. From the results from Table 3 and 4, we observe that there is a performance drop in all models when evaluated on ASR transcripts. This behavior is expected due to the noisy nature of ASR data.
